related_questions.question: What degree do you need to work in a national park?
related_questions.snippet: Most park ranger positions require a four-year bachelor's degree. Rangers may have degrees in recreation and tourism management or environmental education. However, a solid background in earth science, environmental science, and biology is important for work at many locations.
related_questions.title: How to Become a Park Ranger | EnvironmentalScience.org

related_questions.question: How much do you make working at a national park?
related_questions.snippet: National Park Service Salaries of 2017 The National Park Service had 17,846 employees in 2015 with an average pay (base salary + bonus) of $65,213.80. The most common occupation was park ranger, followed by maintenance mechanic. The most common payscale is General Schedule.
related_questions.title: National Park Service Salary Statistics - FederalPay.org

related_questions.question: How do you become a national park ranger?
related_questions.snippet: Steps for Becoming a Park Ranger Prospective park rangers must be US citizens, possess a valid US driver's license, and be at least 21 years of age. Prospective park managers generally have a bachelor's degree in the natural sciences such as botany, zoology, geology, environmental studies, or ecology.
related_questions.title: How to Become a Park Ranger: Career and Salary Information

related_questions.question: How much money does a park ranger make a year?
related_questions.snippet: Park rangers may earn as little as $15 an hour for seasonal work at a small state park to as much as $80,000 a year or more for supervisory positions at large state or national parks. Park ranger jobs may be full-time and year-round, or they may be part-time and seasonal, thus affecting salary ranges.
